40%

Notes:

IMPORTANT: If you are using this in any kind of enclosed or heated chamber, be sure to print it with ABS filament, not PLA. From my experience (as far as I can tell), the heat can make the PLA go soft and make the guard very very difficult to remove if required. I had to use a Dremel to get it off when using PLA.

The thread will print nicer if you use a finer z-resolution so I would recommend 0.1mm, printed with the rounded end up the top. Screw it onto the probe so the bottom of the guard is level with the end of the probe, or just a tad higher.

A 40deg tilt HS1177 mount (with top connector placement) designed for the Multi RC HMB-X5 frame. I highly recommend printing this piece in a flexible filament (TPE and TPU are pictured). Printing in flexible filament ensures a tight fit and can also serve to dampen any oscillations in your FPV feed. The camera is superglued to the printed part and is a very tight fit to both the camera and the standoffs. I use a 2.5mm lens on my HS1177 rather than the stock (for most suppliers) 2.8mm lens.

There is a version with hexagon holes for hexagonal stand offs and one with circular holes for more standard cylindrical standoffs.

-Print the crankshaft standing up. Yes that'll be a lot of support, but it'll print more accurately

-Print the upper crankcase upside down (mating face of the head touching buildplate). This will also generate a lot of support material, but the bearing surfaces for the crankshaft need to be accurate

-Print the connecting rod with the upper hole vertical on the buildplate. Print the rod cap and bearing cap in the same fashion

-Print the piston head with the top of the cylinder against the build plate

-The connecting rod pins are slightly tapered. Make sure the larger diameter end of the pin is against the buildplate

-The lower crankcase can be printed normally with no supports needed

-The connecting rods & rod caps may need some slight sanding/filing to fit into the crankshaft. They should rotate smoothly when put together

-The connecting rod should also rotate freely around the wrist pin

-The engine can only spin one clockwise. Otherwise the pistons will detach from the cylinder walls (not a big deal)

-Lubrication might be a good idea, but I have not tried it

-Printed with a layer height of 0.8mm (pins printed at 0.1mm)

-If everything is goes right, you can spin it up reaaaaally freakin' fast with an electric drill

Assembly Order & Instructions:

  1. Piston Assembly:
    Print Piston heads, connecting rods, and wrist pins
    Line up upper connecting rod hole with piston head hole. Insert and press in wrist pin
    *Connecting rod & piston head should rotate smoothly
  2. Crankshaft Assembly:
    Print the lower crankcase (named Crankcase.stl), bearing caps, and crankshaft
    Place crankshaft onto the lower crankcase and line up the grooves on both the crankshaft and crankcase
    Press bearing caps onto the crankcase pins
    Crankshaft should rotate smoothly
  3. Connecting Rod Assembly:
    This part can be a bit tricky
    Print connecting rod pins
    Slide piston assembly onto crankshaft
    Turn the crankshaft as much as necessary and press in the connecting rod pins
    *Repeat 4X
  4. Upper Crankcase Assembly:
    Print upper crankcase and crankcase pins
    Press crankcase pins half way into the lower crankcase
    With all four pistons attached to the crankshaft, slide the upper crankcase over the pistons, lining up the pistons with the cylinder walls. Pistons may need to be snapped into the cylinder wall
    Press upper crankcase onto lower crankcase pins
    Attach crank lever onto the square hole of the crankshaft
    Make sure everything rotates smoothly, if not, go back and sand/file the necessary parts

description.text:
This is an alternate clip to hold the pieces of Jazzmyn's Customizable Marble Machine together. The clip has a block in the back of it designed to hold a cylindrical magnet. Using these clips with magnets inserted and the track pieces from Jazzmyn's Customizable Marble Machine you can build a marble track that mounts to a ferrous metal surface.

This clip is a much tighter fit on the track pieces than the original clips from Jazzmyn's set. They have a slightly larger lip around the edges and have slightly smaller interior diameter so they grip the track pieces more tightly. My intent was to make the clips grip the rings tightly enough that no zip ties are needed.

I designed this clip to be used with 1/4 inch x 1/4 inch neodymium magnets that I purchased from Applied Magnets. As of the time I write this, these are model #ND014 in the www.magnet4less.com store. You can find these magnets at this link.

The hole for the magnet is a tight fit because I wanted the magnet to stay in the block by friction, even when pulling the clip off of a thick ferrous surface. This means it's somewhat difficult to insert the magnet and requires significant force. The technique I use is to place the cylinder magnet on a hard flat surface, then press the clip down into the magnet with my thumb, pushing down on the inside the ring directly over the block.

We don't usually play the 5-6 version, but if there's enough requests for one I would probably make it. title: RichRap's 3DR - Modified for 8mm Rod and 20mm Box section (Squared Wood, Extruded Aluminium or Box Section Steel)

description.text:
This is a modification of RichRaps excellent 3DR, a Delta type RepRap,
These files have been modified from the default design to allow 8mm diameter rods to replace the 6mm rods of Rich's default design.
The original design was exclusively compatible with extruded aluminium (Misumi / 2020 style) whereas this version will build up with practically anything
This allows for a much taller machine to be built while not suffering from bearing rod deflection.
NEWLY ADDED - A complete model (STL) of a "fully" assembled 3DR for physical reference -
BIGGERER(!) Top and Bottom platform Extensions
A work in progress version of the micro platform built around the E3D Kraken.
An alternate Vertical Carriage with a touch extra clearance for variations in LM8UUs or printed bushings
The primary other change is that the frame has been modified to accept 20mm square box section (much easier to source worldwide - B&Q's easy in the UK), or indeed 20mm square wood as this is FAR more accessible worldwide that extruded aluminium, though in theory almost any material should suffice as long as it has enough lateral strength - I dare someone try carbon fibre poles!
Sizing the rods up to 8mm more than compensates for any structural strength lost by switching out the extruded aluminium for softer materials. So much so, that using high enough quality Steel rods - one can forgo using the 20mm upright legs altogether if you wish... Files included are RichRaps complete (printed) parts list for the 3DR, with direct replacements for the (originally) 6mm parts.
Also included are the files for Ichibey's damn useful rod assembly jig (thing:166605) and the files for Pablogill's 3DR extensions (thing:194631) As well as my own design of BIGGERER extensions ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:215740 ) - All these should allow you to increase the print area of the 3DR in the simplest manner possible... YET ANOTHER ADDENDUM
Richraps' Generally suggested quick calculation for rod lengths is 0.8 x Horizontal distance between the vertical posts (Vp). [which by my tape measure is ~330mm] Other Delta designs go off 2xR Using both equations gives us: 2xR = 256mm (R~128mm approx) OR 0.8xVp = 264mm A difference of 8mm. As long as the rods are all the same length once assembled +/- up to 10mm isn't a problem, You should be fine tuning your firmware to compensate for tolerance variations anyway.
Hope This Helps! P.S. The 3D model uploaded for visual reference is 1000mm tall on the Vertical pillars - this makes no difference to the above calculations, but as someone else asked me why the proportions seem different to the vanilla 3DR, I thought i'd clarify that here.. Thank you for downloading, please be aware and abide by the license. all the files for the RichRap 3DR Delta printer and derivatives are covered by -
Attribution - ShareAlike Creative Commons V3 (CC BY-SA3.0) Much Gratitude to RichRap for his excellent work on this design.
All credit and 'props' where it's due, without his sweat and swearing there would probably be no 'true' Delta Repraps, Just Repstraps..

While the 3DR project home is here:
http://richrap.blogspot.co.uk/2013/07/3dr-reprap-delta-printer-part-1-release.html
The Assembly documentation and such can be found on Richs primary site, Here:
http://richrap.blogspot.co.uk/2013/07/3dr-reprap-delta-printer-part-1-release.html

Aryn CNC is a personal project of building a CNC machine for 3D printing, carving, or PCB drilling. The final should result in a low cost "professional" CNC tool able to work in 50cm x 50cm x 40cm volume (X, Y, Z).

Documentation and STL

Because it's a big project (including a lot of parts, many documentation, feedbacks, etc...) the whole is available on github for better readability

The goals

  • modular : easy to add, remove and update parts => it's for me the most important goal.
  • professional : fast, precise and strong, that's why I chose to use only high quality materials. It increase the price, but he, we want the best no ?
  • 'low' cost : far under the professional market (price estimated around 500$, expensive but not as much as a pro solution). I'm expecting same or better precision.
  • important work volume : 50cm x 50cm x 40cm (aprox) into a 75cm side cube (you should be able to put it in your car). It's a far better ratio than most of the 3D printer (ex: Haeckel 47cm x 47cm x 57cm size for a 20cm x 20cm x 35cm print volume)
  • for makers : if you have time, are handyman, own a 3D printer (or know someone) and like precision, this CNC is done for you.

The machine is not finished yet, but the main hardware parts are done and ready to be used.

Fell free to test, contribute, improve or comment (create issues for that on github).

Please take care of the Apache License before copying/editing the parts. You can use git to download the entire project, edit parts and create pull request or create an issue to share your parts. It would simplify my life not to search improvements on various websites :P

I hope you'll enjoy this project :)

title: Yakima bar end cap with tie-down loop

description.text:
I've always disliked the stock end caps that come with all Yakima roof rack cross-bars. This design fit the bill of a beefier end-cap while providing a handy loop to hook anything to (bungee cord, rope etc). I was amazed at how strong these are and VERY difficult to get off once you smack them on! They are 5.5cm x 3.5cm x 2.5cm tall (when on the build platform)  with nicely rounded edges, especially on the loop so as not to fray any tie-down materials (which made for more complicated polygons and a resulting large-ish .stl file)
We'll see how the UV's out here in Colorado treat them, also, it's cold here now, so we'll also see if there's any change in fit once summer rolls around - but it's always easy enough to print more if I have to!
As with anything, use at your own risk, but I've had great luck with them so far.

I created this using Rhino and printed them one at a time on a heated acrylic platform using ABS (about 50 minutes each) and the latest versions of Skeinfox/Skeinforge updated with the settings found at http://wiki.makerbot.com/configuring-skeinforge I've been building this 'raftless', but am having trouble doing so on my new kapton covered ceramic platform - the 'loop' wants to pop up which it never did on the acrylic platform - and I hate peeling rafts off the bottom of builds. Strength was a main concern here, so I wanted the fills pretty solid. I can fit three of these at once on the build platform and will be trying that soon. I just got my new ceramic heated platform working and will try one on there. I now have some colored ABS and may try some in colors, but feel as though it may draw too much attention = theft :-) I recently designed an even bigger/ beefier version (7cm x 4.5cm x 2.5cm) and will post those soon. They're kind of ridiculously large, but kinda cool.

I have uploaded a few more options for the backplate, it has been brought to my attention that I have my hotend set too high @ 2.7mm, the Micro Swiss manual states that the cold end should protrude 1.7mm so MK2 1.7mm is now available with or without support.

I have downloaded and tested a few of these drive plate and non of the worked for me, I am printing with the Duplicator I3 V2.1 with a micro Swiss hot end.

I have designed this with very high tolerance, just 0.5mm between the main body and the drive gear. I have also built in more spring tension so there is no need to purchase a stronger spring. As you can see in my photos my Micro Swiss sits proud on top of the block so I have allowed for this in the print meaning there is no need to use and PTFE tubing. I have designed this plate so that the re is literally no where for the filament to go except out of the hot end.

You will use the original release leaver and hardware, so just print fit and enjoy printing flex.

description.text:
Règles/Rules (Fr/En)
Fr : Règles
Nombre de joueurs : 1 à 4
Matériel : 12 quilles, un lanceur, un palet
Règle du jeu : Toutes les quilles sont placées serrées les unes aux autres sur le marquage le plus proche du début de table.
Début de partie :
Les quilles se placent dans le cercle
Il est possible à tout moment de la partie de viser des quilles indirectement en se servant des bords de table («bandes»).
Marquage des points:
Si le joueur fait tomber une quille, il marque la valeur de la quille.
S’il fait tomber plusieurs quilles, il marque le nombre de quilles tombées.
Si une quille tombée repose partiellement sur une autre quille, sur un des bords de la table ou sur le palet, elle n’est pas prise en compte dans le score.
Si une ou plusieurs quilles sortent de la table, elles sont remises au centre (marquage du jeu de quilles le plus proche du fond) à leur place attribuée. (Exemple : la «6» sort, elle sera remise sur le chiffre 6 du 2ème marquage ou le 5 si le 6 n’est pas libre etc…).
Le joueur ne marque aucun point et ce coup correspond à un raté. Les quilles tombées sont ensuite relevées sur leur base à l’emplacement où elles se trouvent.
Si une quille revient avant le trait d’appoint, elle sera remise le long de la ligne au même niveau.
Si un joueur ne marque aucun point trois fois de suite, il est éliminé.

La partie se termine lorsqu’un joueur obtient exactement 50 points.
Si un joueur marque plus de 50 points, son score redescendra à 25 points et il continuera à jouer.

D’après une conception de : Patrick PIRIOU
Rendu imprimable par : Aurélien DHAUSSY

En : Rules
Number of players: 1 to 4

Materials: 12 pins, a pitcher, a puck

Rule of the game: All pins are placed tightly together on the marking closest to the start of the table.

Start of game:
The pins are placed in the circle
It is possible at any time of the game to aim for pins indirectly by using the table edges ("bands").

Marking points:
If the player drops a keel, it marks the value of the keel.
If he knocks several skittles, he marks the number of skittles fallen.
If a fallen keel rests partially on another keel, on one of the edges of the table or on the puck, it is not taken into account in the score.

If one or more skittles leave the table, they are put back in the center (marking the set of pins closest to the bottom) to their assigned place. (Example: the "6" goes out, it will be given on the number 6 of the 2nd marking or the 5 if the 6 is not free etc ...).

The player does not score any points and this shot is a misfire. The fallen keels are then raised on their base at the location where they are located.

If a keel returns before the extra line, it will be delivered along the line at the same level.

If a player scores no points three times in a row, he is eliminated.

The game ends when a player gets exactly 50 points.
If a player scores more than 50 points, his score will drop to 25 points and he will continue to play.

According to a design by: Patrick PIRIOU
Rendered by: Aurélien DHAUSSY

title: Modular Slim Urban Terrain
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I am a great fan of Dutchmogul (http://www.thingiverse.com/dutchmogul/about) and devonjones (http://www.thingiverse.com/devonjones/about) here in Thingiverse, and I have been collecting their excellent designs avidly, I encourage all to look into their stuff! It is pretty awesome and only gets better the more time passes. I thank you both, for the years of inspiration and great content

Lately, I have been craving to play some of my tabletop games, and I found myself in acute need of terrain. I needed a lot, and I needed it fast, for a minimum amount of money of course.
The only drawback with the dungeon tiles found here, and other gaming terrains, in my opinion, is that they are quite robust and require a lot of material. Looking at the very thick walls of the first Wayfarer Tactics terrain set and comparatively thinner pillars I thought that there was an issue with the proportion of one to the other. So I used the pillar as the main structure and made thin walls to match. Aside from that, there is a remarkable amount of gaming mats today that render the printing of floors redundant, unless you want to replicate specific terrain types. So I made due with just pillars and walls, getting an inexpensive type of terrain that can be print in generous amounts with next to no filament.

I hope you enjoy it and I wish you happy gaming!

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 or thicker for faster prints

Infill:

0

Notes:

Print standing up with the small side of the wall facing the build platform, these walls are not made to print flat on the build platform as they are textured on both sides. Be sure to use a brim so that the flat wall sections stay in place and do not fall, if you have a heated build plate you will have an easier time getting perfectly straight wall section.

2 shells are more than enough to create stable and sturdy wall sections. Make sure to have at least 3 top and bottom shells to ensure part integrity.

I basically used Dutchmoguls pillar design and cut slots into it that would allow for wall sections to be inserted, instantly creating useful, light, and easy to assemble building that offered much customization.

The wall sections have a base thickness 0f 2.5 mm and a height of 60 mm. I did not pay attention to the length of the wall sections, in case you need wall sections in specific lengths for games that use a grid, feel free to make your own or scale them non-uniformly to suit your purposes.

All details on the walls were extruded from the basic wall element just a couple of tenths of a millimeter, this has worked really well and is more than enough to create a good level of surface detail. More intricate designs are very possible and I encourage you, if you so decide, to make some!

Use 5 edge pieces and 4 external center pieces and fit them between the internal centers. You will be left with a hole where the "last piece" can be fitted. title: Milano Social Housing - Structure and Design

description.text:
{ Check out the full version of this project at:
http://messiosmarios.com/hybrid-revitalization.html

There is also a walk-through visualisation of the design (I call it THE GAME)
You can play online a demo online or download the full game on windows and mac
https://messiosmarios.itch.io/milano-housing
Please follow the instruction on the website
}

architectural visualisation and naked structure - for a social housing project developed at the Politecnico di Milano.​

The proposal envisions total demolition of the existing buildings of one of the sectors not because they do not have any significant architectural value, identity or spatial quality but for this form of energy and structural study it is suffice to do so.

On the thus vacant site we propose a complex of buildings with a configuration, which reminds somehow the previous urban texture of the area, but at the same time allows to improve the traffic problem on the adjacent crossroad, opens passages and views to the park, and increases density of the dwellings.
The provided dwellings differ in size, type and configuration, thus stimulating the diversity among the inhabitants (students sharing apartments, persons living alone, small and big families, artists living in their workplace, etc.).
On the east side of the design is as a result of two twin buildings, twisting in front of each other, thus creating a communal courtyard of an interesting shape, adapted for undisturbed coexistence of various activities. For the programmatic distribution the gallery-system is chosen (as a reference to the previously existing typology on site, but also due to the economical and functional advantages of the gallery distribution).
The ground floor of the buildings is used for various shops and services. the rest of the building is solidly residential. the height of the building varies from five to four storeys, the roof is foreseen to be livable (duplex apartments and mansards).
The west side is composed of two linear elements.
The primary one is designed as a series of workshops & laboratories (a function that already existed on that same place) with an attic level and compact facilities block for living.
The second element consists of a platform with stores and services, and a residential tower of four floors with a habitable roof.
For both blocks an underground parking on one level is foreseen.
Photovoltaic panels are placed on the sloped roofs of both the blocks, oriented to south & southwest, in order to provide the energy needed, to classify the buildings to the label a/b.
The structure is made out of steel, with concrete cores and shear walls. for the facades, metal panelling combined with steel framed windows.
THe steel chosen is IPE 300 for primary beams and HEA 200 for secondary beams. Reinforced concrete for the cores and the blind shear walls. Calculations shown in the document below.

title: anet a6 - auto level sensor mount - with bonus fan grille!

description.text:
Trying to mount an auto level sensor on my anet a6.
I managed to mount it on the right-hand side (from the front), but it was blocking the X-axis going to full 220mm. This is another attempt - this time mounting from the front, using the fan grille mounting screws.

If you print it out, let me know in the comments if it works for you, or if there is a different sensor you want to mount.

There is a version without the grille, but I couldn't install it without longer screws or removing the stock grille, so.....

.... I created a custom fan grille and combined them together. I've also turned the sensor mount around so it can mount in the centre.

The next step is running the wire, getting the A6 firmware set up and calibrating the unit. If anyone out there has done this before, I'll trade you my cool sensor mount for tips on how to make it work.

The included gcode version of the sensor mount and grille is exactly what I printed - for some reason craftware sliced it up for a better result than repetier, and a quicker print - it includes some supports under the overhang and in the screw slots - its printed at a resolution of 0.1mm, because it's going to be bolted on the front of your print head where you'll see it all the time, so it might as well be purdy.

Remove your original grille by removing the two allen-key nuts at the bottom of the fan, and then put the cool new grille in place.

Attach the sensor with 18x3mm bolts - have the nut on the sensor end, and the screw head in the slot in the mount.

Now.... who knows how to program this thing?

Update: I've added another version with a round mount clip for the other common sensor type. I don't have one, so let me know if it needs any adjustments.

title: Vortex Generator for RC Plane / Wing Reptile S800 Sky Shadow

description.text:
This is a vortex generator (VG) i designed for the Reptile S800 Sky Shadow FPV RC flying wing. Although they can be used on any RC plane.
.
DON'T BE SPECIAL AND USE THEM ON A REAL PLANE!!!
.
.
.
There are 2 types. 1 that can be double sided sticky taped on to the wing, temporarily to test the vortex generators and a 2nd which can be inserted into a small slit you make in the wing and glued in place once you are happy with it position and functionality.
.
.
The plane fly's amazingly! But, as it's quite heavy and has the glide ratio of a brick when you cut the throttle to land especially when its fully loaded with a 2200mah lipo, GoPro (Sj4000 or Andoer 4K Action Cam are just as good) and all the other bits, i thought it could do with a bit of help landing a bit slower. So theres no simpler way than a VG.
.
I have tested these and stall speed has been decreased dramatically! Control at low speed and high alpha are also significantly improved. This makes for a much slower and controlled landing.
.
.
.
.
If you don't know what a VG is, in short, it delays local flow separation. Decreasing stall speed and increasing low speed control.
.
Here is a good video that explains them very well https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Whd_KnsLKE
.
To set them up correctly, they need to be at 15 degrees relative to the direction of the aircraft flight direction, NOT the wing! The S800 Reptile has a 30 Degree wing sweep. I recommend spacing 6 VG's out over each wing at 60mm apart and 20mm back from the leading edge. Please see photos for a visual aid.
.
This is just a guide. Feel free to experiment however you like.
.
If you print some out, please upload a photo as id love to see it!
.
.
Print at 0.1mm layer height and 100% infill
.
.
.
.
.
Warhog has designed some genius little tools to help place your vortex generators at the correct distance and angle on the Skyshadow S800. You can download his awesome design here https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2544706

title: MBS All Terrain Skate Wheel Conversion Kit for Boosted Boards V2

description.text:
This design includes a gear pulley for mounting "All Terrain" longboard wheels from MBS to a Boosted Boards V2 electric skateboard, and a replacement belt cover cap which has more clearance for the larger gear. You'll also need QTY 2 of this belt: Gates 255-3MGT-15, and QTY 2 of this bearing: B6903ZZ. You'll probably want to pick up a set of standard skate bearings and spacers too, so you don't have to swap that between sets of wheels when you swap from stock wheels to AT and vice versa. For the other hardware (axle nuts, speed rings, washers, cap mount screws) you can reuse the stock hardware.

We created this design for R&D, but we've decided not to pursue it further. This design is a working prototype, but it can't be guaranteed that a 3d printed gear hub can handle the torque of real world riding for very long, or that a 3d printed belt cover will survive rocks, debris, or other impacts. Print, assemble, and test at your own risk. Please be careful. Always wear a helmet when riding.

Our prototypes are printed in ABS with 100% infill. If you print the gear as is, you won't need supports, but it may be difficult to remove from the print bed. I would suggest trying it upside down with supports. The belt cover cap requires supports.
